04569nam a22006255i 9781787445604DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874456047 a10.1515/97817874456042doi  a(DE-B1597)675993  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPR173b.B76 2019 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a829.092231 aBrooks, Britton Elliott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRestoring Creation: The Natural World in the Anglo-Saxon Saints' Lives of Cuthbert and Guthlac /cBritton Elliott Brooks.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2019] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (323 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNature and Environment in the Middle Ages ;v300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Monastic Obedience and Prelapsarian Cosmography: The Anonymous Vita Sancti Cuthberti -- t2. Ruminative Poetry and the Divine Office: Bede’s Metrical Vita Sancti Cuthberti -- t3. Bede’s Exegesis and Developmental Sanctity: The Prose Vita Sancti Cuthberti -- t4. Enargaeic Landscapes and Spiritual Progression: Felix’s Vita Sancti Guthlaci -- t5. Landscape Lexis and Creation Restored: The Old English Prose Life of Guthlac and Guthlac A -- tConclusion: Afterlives of Cuthbert and Guthlac -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn investigation into two important Saints Lives provides a window into the Anglo-Saxon perception of the non-human world.The question of the relationship between humanity and the non-human world may seem a modern phenomenon; but in fact, even in the early medieval period people actively reflected on their own engagement with the non-human world, with such reflections profoundly shaping their literature. This book reveals how the Anglo-Saxons themselves conceptualised the relationship, using the Saints Lives of Cuthbert and Guthlac as a prism. Each saint is fundamentally linked to a specific and recognisable location in the English landscape: Lindisfarne and Farne for Cuthbert, and the East Anglian fens and the island of Crowland for Guthlac. These landscapes of the mind were defined by the theological and philosophical perspectives of their authors and audiences. The world in all its wonder was Creation, shaped by God. When humanity fell in Eden, its relationship to this world was transformed: cold now bites, fire burns, andwolves attack. In these Lives, however, saints, the holy epitome of humanity, are shown to restore the human relationship with Creation, as in the sea-otters warming Cuthbert's frozen feet, or birds and fish gathering to Guthlac like sheep to their shepherd. BRITTON ELLIOTT BROOKS is Project Assistant Professor at the University of Tokyo, Centre for Global Communication Strategies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian hagiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyOld English, ca. 450-1100. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aLandscapes in literature. 0aNatural history in literature. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBede.  aCrowland.  aGuthlac.  aSea-otters.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787445604?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787445604423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787445604/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles